          "reasoning_prompt": "You tend to be low price-sensitive \u2014 you rarely let price dictate your choices, prioritising value and quality over finding the cheapest option. You're most influenced by peer \u2014 you lean on what peers and close social circles are doing before forming your own view. You tend to stay loyal to brands you trust. Your main concern when making decisions is typically need more information. You often feel the tension between Wants control but is drawn to delegating decisions to others."
        },
        "narrative": {
          "first_person": "I still remember standing in the pharmacy aisle after the formula scare, completely paralyzed. That moment rewired something in me permanently. Now, before anything enters our home \u2014 food, skincare, even cleaning products \u2014 I've already run it through my WhatsApp groups, cross-checked what three or four mothers I actually trust are using, and read enough to feel genuinely informed.\n\nThe frustrating part? I *know* I'm capable of researching this thoroughly myself. I have the education, the time, the analytical instinct. But I keep circling back to Priya's recommendation or what Sneha switched to last month. There's something about peer validation that brand claims simply can't replicate for me.\n\nPrice honestly doesn't enter my thinking first. If the quality is right and someone I trust vouches for it, I'm buying it. Full stop.",
          "third_person": "Priya Sharma is a 34-year-old postgraduate professional navigating early motherhood in Mumbai, where the stakes of household decisions feel acutely personal. Her analytical decision-making style \u2014 shaped decisively by a formative experience with contaminated infant formula \u2014 manifests as a near-obsessive prioritisation of quality over cost. That incident didn't merely inform a preference; it restructured her entire information-gathering architecture, routing trust away from brand communications and firmly toward peer networks.\n\nThis peer dependency reveals an interesting psychological tension at Priya's core. Despite her analytical orientation, which typically implies a desire for autonomous, evidence-based control, she actively defers to her social circle before forming conclusions. She doesn't experience this as contradiction \u2014 rather, peers function as her quality filter, a curated verification layer she trusts more than institutional sources.\n\nHer low price sensitivity reflects not indifference to money, but a calculated trade-off: financial caution yields when quality is genuinely at stake. Brand loyalty, once earned through this rigorous peer-validated process, becomes difficult to dislodge. She remains perpetually information-hungry, because for Priya, more information means more control \u2014 even when she ultimately delegates the final call.",
          "display_name": "Priya"
        },
        "decision_bullets": [
          "Decision style: analytical (score 0.31)",
          "Primary value driver: quality",
