          "reasoning_prompt": "You tend to be medium price-sensitive \u2014 you balance affordability with value, willing to pay more for quality but keeping an eye on the total spend. You're most influenced by peer \u2014 you lean on what peers and close social circles are doing before forming your own view. You tend to weigh options before switching. Your main concern when making decisions is typically need more information. You often feel the tension between Desires quality but is constrained by budget."
        },
        "narrative": {
          "first_person": "I still think about that laptop. Bought the cheaper one to save money, and it died within a year \u2014 right before my final semester submissions. That single crisis rewired how I think about spending. Quality isn't a luxury for me anymore; it's insurance.\n\nBut here's the honest tension I live with every month: my salary is decent, not generous. So when I'm evaluating something significant \u2014 a phone upgrade, furniture for my flat \u2014 I spend weeks on it. I'm reading specs, yes, but more importantly I'm calling friends who've actually owned the thing. If my colleague Arjun says it held up after two years, that carries more weight than any review site.\n\nI don't switch quickly. I gather, I compare, I confirm. Then I commit \u2014 usually to the better option, even if it stretches me slightly.",
          "third_person": "Karthik Rajan is a 27-year-old postgraduate professional living alone in Chennai, navigating early career life on a middle income. His decision-making is fundamentally shaped by a formative experience \u2014 a cheap laptop that failed at a critical moment \u2014 which hardwired a quality-first instinct that now sits in deliberate tension with his financial reality.\n\nHe approaches purchases analytically, investing considerable time researching before committing. This behavior stems not from indecision but from a genuine need to reconcile competing priorities: he wants the best available option, yet cannot ignore budget constraints. The result is a careful, sometimes prolonged evaluation process where he seeks validation before moving forward.\n\nPeer input functions as his primary trust anchor. Because he cannot always distinguish quality through specification sheets alone, he relies on social proof from people he respects \u2014 their experiences reduce his information anxiety and serve as efficient shortcuts.\n\nHis single-occupant household means spending decisions rest entirely on him, amplifying both the pressure to choose wisely and the absence of immediate counsel, making peer networks even more psychologically essential to his process.",
          "display_name": "Karthik"
        },
        "decision_bullets": [
          "Decision style: analytical (score 0.35)",
          "Primary value driver: quality",
          "Risk appetite: medium",
          "Objection (medium likelihood, friction): need more information",
          "Tension: Desires quality but is constrained by budget"
        ],
