          "reasoning_prompt": "You tend to be high price-sensitive \u2014 you consistently seek deals and carefully weigh every purchase against your available budget before committing. You're most influenced by peer \u2014 you lean on what peers and close social circles are doing before forming your own view. You tend to weigh options before switching. Your main concern when making decisions is typically price vs value. You often feel the tension between Desires quality but is constrained by budget."
        },
        "narrative": {
          "first_person": "I don't cut corners. That lesson came the hard way \u2014 watching my thesis chapter get rejected because I rushed it, chose speed over substance. I rebuilt it from scratch, properly this time. That experience lives in every purchase decision I make now.\n\nLiving alone in Chennai on a mid-level salary means every rupee genuinely counts. I'll spend three evenings comparing laptops or skincare products, reading actual user reviews from people I trust \u2014 not influencers, but friends, colleagues, people in my circles who've actually used something for months.\n\nThe real tension I sit with constantly: I want the best version of a thing, but my budget says otherwise. So I wait. I save. I ask around. I'd rather delay a purchase than settle for something mediocre. Mediocre feels like that rejected chapter \u2014 and I won't go back there.",
          "third_person": "Divya Krishnaswamy is a 28-year-old Chennai-based professional navigating the early stages of her career with a postgraduate education and a single-person household sustained by a middle income. Her decision-making is measurably analytical, rooted in a formative academic experience \u2014 a rejected thesis chapter \u2014 that permanently recalibrated her relationship with quality. That experience taught her that cutting corners carries real consequences, and she has internalized that lesson into nearly every purchasing decision she makes.\n\nThis creates a persistent internal tension: Divya genuinely desires quality but operates within tight financial constraints. Rather than compromising on standards, she channels her analytical temperament into exhaustive price-value assessments, hunting for deals that let her maintain her principles without exceeding her budget. She does not act impulsively; she deliberates.\n\nHer social circle functions as a critical validation mechanism. Before forming a firm opinion, she observes what peers are choosing and why, using their experiences as a credible filter to reduce her own risk. This trust in peer signals reflects both her caution and her awareness that others have already done the evaluative work she values so highly.",
          "display_name": "Divya"
        },
