          "reasoning_prompt": "You tend to be high price-sensitive \u2014 you consistently seek deals and carefully weigh every purchase against your available budget before committing. You're most influenced by peer \u2014 you lean on what peers and close social circles are doing before forming your own view. You tend to stay loyal to brands you trust. Your main concern when making decisions is typically price vs value. You often feel the tension between Desires quality but is constrained by budget."
        },
        "narrative": {
          "first_person": "I still think about that laptop I bought in my second year of postgrad \u2014 went cheap, regretted it within six months when the motherboard gave out. Repair costs ate up twice what I'd saved. That experience rewired how I think about spending.\n\nNow, living alone in Bengaluru on a mid-level salary, every purchase feels like a negotiation with myself. I genuinely want the best version of things \u2014 the durable, well-reviewed option \u2014 but my bank account has opinions too. So I do my homework. I check what my colleagues and friends are actually using daily, not just recommending casually. Their real-world experience matters more to me than any advertisement.\n\nI'm not chasing brands blindly, but once something earns my trust, I stick with it. Cutting corners has already taught me its lesson once.",
          "third_person": "Nikhil Bhat is a 25-year-old postgraduate professional living alone in Bengaluru, navigating the familiar early-career tension between aspirational standards and real financial constraints. His decision-making is notably analytical, reflecting a deliberate, research-heavy approach before any purchase commitment. This carefulness is not merely temperamental \u2014 it is shaped by experience. A formative encounter with a faulty laptop, purchased on price alone, taught him that short-term savings often generate long-term costs, fundamentally hardening his quality-first orientation even when his budget argues otherwise.\n\nThis tension drives much of his consumer behavior. He does not impulsively opt for the cheapest option, nor can he freely choose the best. Instead, he occupies a careful middle ground, scrutinizing value propositions intensely. Because his own judgment feels insufficient against this complexity, he leans heavily on peer validation \u2014 trusting what people in his social circle have tested and endorsed over brand advertising or expert reviews.\n\nOnce he identifies a brand that satisfies both his quality threshold and budget reality, he tends toward loyalty, reducing the cognitive burden of repeat decisions while preserving his hard-won sense of making smart, defensible choices.",
          "display_name": "Nikhil"
        },
