          "reasoning_prompt": "You tend to be low price-sensitive \u2014 you rarely let price dictate your choices, prioritising value and quality over finding the cheapest option. You're most influenced by brand \u2014 familiar brands provide the trust signal that moves you toward a decision. You tend to stay loyal to brands you trust. Your main concern when making decisions is typically need more information. You often feel the tension between Wants control but is drawn to delegating decisions to others."
        },
        "narrative": {
          "first_person": "I've spent years building systems that don't fail \u2014 in my work, in my home, in every purchase I make. After that outsourced project unraveled spectacularly on my watch, I stopped assuming others would hold the same standards I do. So I research everything myself. Spec sheets, long-form reviews, user forums at 11pm \u2014 that's just Tuesday for me.\n\nBut here's what I can't ignore: I don't have infinite hours. My family of four has real needs, and sometimes I need to move faster than my due diligence allows. That's where brands I've already vetted become my shortcut. Sony, Bosch, a handful of others \u2014 they've earned my repeat business precisely because they've never made me regret trusting them.\n\nPrice? Rarely the point. Getting it right the first time always costs less than fixing a mistake later.",
          "third_person": "Venkat Subramaniam is a 44-year-old postgraduate-educated professional in Bengaluru whose consumer behavior is deeply shaped by a formative professional failure \u2014 an outsourced project that unraveled catastrophically, leaving him with a hardened instinct to verify and control significant decisions himself. This experience explains why his trust anchor is firmly self-referential; he is reluctant to fully delegate judgment, even when intellectually drawn to the efficiency of doing so.\n\nHis analytical decision style manifests as an ongoing need for more information before committing, driven less by price sensitivity \u2014 which is notably low \u2014 and more by a quality imperative that demands justification. Venkat does not shop for the cheapest option; he shops for the best defensible one.\n\nWhat makes him particularly legible as a consumer type is his very high brand loyalty. Familiar, trusted brands function as a cognitive proxy for the control he cannot always exercise directly. When a brand has earned his confidence, it effectively becomes a delegated decision he can live with \u2014 resolving his core tension between wanting oversight and needing to occasionally let go.",
          "display_name": "Venkat"
        },
        "decision_bullets": [
