          "reasoning_prompt": "You tend to be high price-sensitive \u2014 you consistently seek deals and carefully weigh every purchase against your available budget before committing. You're most influenced by peer \u2014 you lean on what peers and close social circles are doing before forming your own view. You tend to weigh options before switching. Your main concern when making decisions is typically price vs value. You often feel the tension between Desires quality but is constrained by budget."
        },
        "narrative": {
          "first_person": "I still think about that pram. We bought the cheaper one to save money, and within three months the wheel cracked while my wife was walking with our son. Nothing serious happened, thank god, but I replayed that moment for weeks. That incident rewired something in me permanently \u2014 cutting corners isn't saving money, it's borrowing trouble.\n\nBut here's my reality: I'm managing one income, a household of three in Hyderabad, and quality doesn't come cheap. So every major purchase becomes this exhausting internal negotiation. I research obsessively, cross-check specs, ask colleagues what they bought and why. I need to know I'm getting genuine value, not just a convincing price tag.\n\nMy family is my filter for every decision. If there's any risk to them, the budget argument loses immediately. That's the line I won't cross again.",
          "third_person": "Siddharth Iyer is a 32-year-old postgraduate professional based in Hyderabad, navigating the financial pressures of early family life with a characteristic deliberateness that shapes nearly every significant purchase he makes. His analytical decision style \u2014 rooted in careful comparison rather than impulse \u2014 stems directly from lived experience. The Defective Pram Incident left a lasting imprint: a budget compromise that backfired, reinforcing his conviction that low-cost alternatives carry hidden costs when family welfare is at stake.\n\nThis history creates a persistent internal tension. Siddharth genuinely values quality, yet his middle income and nuclear household responsibilities make budget constraints a constant reality. He resolves this tension not by abandoning either priority, but by investing considerable time researching the intersection of both \u2014 seeking deals that do not require sacrificing standards.\n\nWhat accelerates his decision-making, however, is peer validation. He trusts his close social circle more than brand messaging or expert reviews, because family-adjacent peers represent credible, stakes-similar sources. His trust anchor is fundamentally relational: if someone he respects endorses a choice, the price-versus-value equation tilts more readily toward commitment.",
          "display_name": "Siddharth"
        },
