  "sarvam_enrichment": [
    {
      "enrichment_applied": true,
      "enrichment_provider": "sarvam",
      "enrichment_scope": "narrative_and_examples",
      "persona_id": "pg-pg-002",
      "enriched_narrative": {
        "first_person": "I still remember standing in the Chemist aisle at my local Worli D-Mart after the formula scare, completely paralyzed. That moment rewired something in me permanently. Now, before anything enters our home \u2014 food, skincare, even cleaning products \u2014 I've already run it through my mothers' WhatsApp group, cross-checked what three or four mothers I actually trust are using on the moms' forum, and read enough reviews on 1mg to feel genuinely informed.\n\nThe frustrating part? I *know* I'm capable of researching this thoroughly myself. I have the education, the time, the analytical instinct. But I keep circling back to Priya's recommendation or what Sneha switched to last month. There's something about peer validation that brand claims simply can't replicate for me.\n\nPrice honestly doesn't enter my thinking first. If the quality is right and someone I trust vouches for it, I'm buying it. Full stop.",
        "third_person": "Priya Sharma is a 34-year-old postgraduate professional navigating early motherhood in Mumbai's upper-middle-class neighborhoods, where the stakes of household decisions feel acutely personal. Her analytical decision-making style \u2014 shaped decisively by a formative experience with contaminated infant formula discovered through trusted mothers' WhatsApp networks \u2014 manifests as a near-obsessive prioritisation of quality over cost. That incident didn't merely inform a preference; it restructured her entire information-gathering architecture, routing trust away from brand communications and firmly toward peer networks and platforms like 1mg.\n\nThis peer dependency reveals an interesting psychological tension at Priya's core. Despite her analytical orientation, which typically implies a desire for autonomous, evidence-based control, she actively defers to her social circle before forming conclusions. She doesn't experience this as contradiction \u2014 rather, peers function as her quality filter, a curated verification layer she trusts more than institutional sources or advertising.\n\nHer low price sensitivity reflects not indifference to money, but a calculated trade-off: financial caution yields when quality is genuinely at stake. Brand loyalty, once earned through this rigorous peer-validated process, becomes difficult to dislodge. She remains perpetually information-hungry, because for Priya, more information means more control \u2014 even when she ultimately delegates the final call."
      },
      "cultural_references_added": [
        "Chemist aisle (regional pharmacy terminology, Mumbai-specific)",
        "Worli D-Mart (specific Mumbai retail location and upper-middle-income shopping anchor)",
        "1mg (India's leading online pharmacy review and information platform, matches urban professional behavior)",
        "mothers' WhatsApp group (authentic peer network medium for Indian urban mothers)",
        "moms' forum (Indian digital community platform for parenting information)"
      ],
      "contextual_examples_replaced": [
        {
          "original": "pharmacy aisle",
          "replacement": "Chemist aisle at my local Worli D-Mart",
          "attribute_source": "location.city, income_bracket (upper-middle), household.structure (nuclear, early-family)"
