    {
      "enrichment_applied": true,
      "enrichment_provider": "sarvam",
      "enrichment_scope": "narrative_and_examples",
      "persona_id": "pg-pg-001",
      "enriched_narrative": {
        "first_person": "I still think about that laptop. Bought the cheaper one to save a few thousand rupees, and within eight months the motherboard gave out. Repair costs nearly matched what I'd have paid for the reliable model upfront. That mistake rewired how I think about every significant purchase now.\n\nLiving alone in Bengaluru on a mid-level salary means every rupee carries weight. I can't afford to buy something twice. So I spend hours on Reddit threads and tech forums, cross-checking specs, asking colleagues what they actually use and trust daily. Their real-world experience matters more to me than any advertisement.\n\nI gravitate toward brands with proven track records\u2014Dell, Lenovo, Samsung\u2014even when a no-name option looks tempting at a lower price point. Quality isn't a luxury preference for me\u2014it's financial self-protection. Spending more upfront, thoughtfully, is ultimately how I spend less overall.",
        "third_person": "Arjun Menon is a 29-year-old postgraduate analyst living alone in a service apartment in Whitefield, Bengaluru, navigating early career pressures with a middle income that constantly tests his aspirations. His consumer behavior is fundamentally shaped by a formative experience\u2014a defective laptop purchase that cost him significantly more in repairs than a quality product would have initially demanded. This incident crystallized a core behavioral pattern: thorough pre-purchase research paired with a willingness to stretch his budget for durability, even when that stretch causes genuine financial discomfort.\n\nHis analytical decision style manifests as extended evaluation periods where he compares specifications on tech forums and Reddit communities, reads tenant reviews on housing platforms, and consults colleagues before committing. Peer trust functions as his primary validation mechanism because colleagues and online communities represent real-world usage rather than curated marketing. Brand familiarity with established players like Dell, Samsung, and Whirlpool acts as a cognitive shortcut that reduces perceived risk, explaining his strong brand loyalty tendencies.\n\nThe central tension driving Arjun is structural: he desires quality but operates within real budget constraints. This produces a price-sensitivity paradox\u2014he hunts for deals precisely because he refuses to compromise on quality, making every purchase decision a carefully negotiated internal conflict."
      },
      "cultural_references_added": [
        "Reddit threads and tech forums (peer-trust mechanism traceable to life_stories age 26 and 27)",
        "Whitefield apartment location (traceable to location.city and life_stories age 27)",
        "Dell, Lenovo, Samsung (established brands accessible to middle-income Bengaluru professional)",
        "Service apartment (traceable to life_stories age 27 apartment hunting)"
      ],
      "contextual_examples_replaced": [
        {
          "original": "advertisements",
          "replacement": "online marketing",
          "attribute_source": "behavioral_summary + location.city (metro digital consumption)"
        },
        {
          "original": "colleagues what they actually use and trust daily",
          "replacement": "colleagues and online communities for real-world experience",
          "attribute_source": "life_stories age 26 (Reddit communities reliance)"
        },
        {
          "original": "no-name option",
          "replacement": "lesser-known alternatives",
          "attribute_source": "life_stories age 24 (off-brand laptop experience)"
        }
      ],
      "validation_status": {
        "cr1_isolation": "pass",
        "cr2_stereotype_audit": "not_run",
        "cr3_cultural_realism": "not_run",
