    },
    {
      "enrichment_applied": true,
      "enrichment_provider": "sarvam",
      "enrichment_scope": "narrative_and_examples",
      "persona_id": "pg-pg-003",
      "enriched_narrative": {
        "first_person": "I still think about that laptop. Bought the cheaper one to save money, and it died within a year \u2014 right before my final semester submissions at Anna University. That single crisis rewired how I think about spending. Quality isn't a luxury for me anymore; it's insurance.\n\nBut here's the honest tension I live with every month: my salary is decent, not generous. So when I'm evaluating something significant \u2014 a phone upgrade, furniture for my flat in Velachery \u2014 I spend weeks on it. I'm reading specs on 91mobiles, yes, but more importantly I'm calling friends who've actually owned the thing. If my colleague Arjun says it held up after two years, that carries more weight than any GSMArena review.\n\nI don't switch quickly. I gather, I compare, I confirm. Then I commit \u2014 usually to the better option, even if it stretches me slightly.",
        "third_person": "Karthik Rajan is a 27-year-old postgraduate professional living alone in a Velachery flat in Chennai, navigating early career life on a middle income in IT. His decision-making is fundamentally shaped by a formative experience \u2014 a cheap no-brand laptop that failed during his Anna University final semester \u2014 which hardwired a quality-first instinct that now sits in deliberate tension with his financial reality.\n\nHe approaches purchases analytically, investing considerable time researching through colleague networks and forums like IndianRedditors and tech communities before committing. This behavior stems not from indecision but from a genuine need to reconcile competing priorities: he wants the best available option, yet cannot ignore budget constraints. The result is a careful, sometimes prolonged evaluation process where he seeks validation from his peer circle before moving forward.\n\nPeer input functions as his primary trust anchor. Because he cannot always distinguish quality through specification sheets alone, he relies on social proof from people he respects \u2014 their experiences reduce his information anxiety and serve as efficient shortcuts in his analytical decision-making."
      },
      "cultural_references_added": [
