    {
      "enrichment_applied": true,
      "enrichment_provider": "sarvam",
      "enrichment_scope": "narrative_and_examples",
      "persona_id": "pg-pg-010",
      "enriched_narrative": {
        "first_person": "I don't cut corners. That lesson came the hard way \u2014 watching my Anna University thesis chapter get rejected because I rushed it, chose speed over substance. I rebuilt it from scratch, properly this time. That experience lives in every purchase decision I make now.\n\nLiving alone in Velachery on a mid-level salary means every rupee genuinely counts. I'll spend three evenings comparing laptops on Flipkart or Nykaa skincare products, reading actual user reviews from people I trust \u2014 not Instagram influencers, but friends, colleagues, people in my circles who've actually used something for months.\n\nThe real tension I sit with constantly: I want the best version of a thing, but my budget says otherwise. So I wait. I save. I ask around. I'd rather delay a purchase than settle for something mediocre. Mediocre feels like that rejected chapter \u2014 and I won't go back there.",
        "third_person": "Divya Krishnaswamy is a 28-year-old Chennai-based professional navigating the early stages of her career with a postgraduate degree from Anna University and a single-person household in Velachery sustained by a middle income. Her decision-making is measurably analytical, rooted in a formative academic experience \u2014 a rejected thesis chapter \u2014 that permanently recalibrated her relationship with quality. That experience taught her that cutting corners carries real consequences, and she has internalized that lesson into nearly every purchasing decision she makes.\n\nThis creates a persistent internal tension: Divya genuinely desires quality but operates within tight financial constraints. Rather than compromising on standards, she channels her analytical temperament into exhaustive price-value assessments across platforms like Flipkart and Amazon, hunting for deals that let her maintain her principles without exceeding her budget. She does not act impulsively; she deliberates.\n\nHer carefully vetted social circle functions as a critical validation mechanism. Before forming a firm opinion, she observes what peers in Chennai are choosing and why, using their lived experiences as a credible filter to reduce her own risk."
      },
      "cultural_references_added": [
        "Anna University (dissertation institution, Chennai-specific)",
