    {
      "enrichment_applied": true,
      "enrichment_provider": "sarvam",
      "enrichment_scope": "narrative_and_examples",
      "persona_id": "pg-pg-013",
      "enriched_narrative": {
        "first_person": "I still think about that laptop I bought in my second year of postgrad \u2014 went cheap, regretted it within six months when the motherboard gave out. Repair costs at the service center ate up twice what I'd saved. That experience rewired how I think about spending.\n\nNow, living alone in Bengaluru on a mid-level salary, every purchase feels like a negotiation with myself. I genuinely want the best version of things \u2014 the durable, well-reviewed option \u2014 but my bank account has opinions too. So I do my homework. I check what my colleagues and friends are actually using daily, not just recommending casually. Their real-world experience matters more to me than any advertisement.\n\nI'm not chasing brands blindly, but once something earns my trust, I stick with it. Cutting corners has already taught me its lesson once.",
        "third_person": "Nikhil Bhat is a 25-year-old postgraduate professional living alone in Bengaluru, navigating the familiar early-career tension between aspirational standards and real financial constraints in India's most expensive metro outside the National Capital Region. His decision-making is notably analytical, reflecting a deliberate, research-heavy approach before any purchase commitment. This carefulness is not merely temperamental \u2014 it is shaped by experience. A formative encounter with a faulty budget laptop, purchased on price alone, taught him that short-term savings often generate long-term costs, fundamentally hardening his quality-first orientation even when his salary argues otherwise.\n\nThis tension drives much of his consumer behavior. He does not impulsively opt for the cheapest option at local retailers, nor can he freely choose premium. Instead, he occupies a careful middle ground, scrutinizing value propositions intensely through online reviews and peer networks. Because his own judgment feels insufficient against this complexity, he leans heavily on peer validation \u2014 trusting what people in his social circle have tested and endorsed over brand advertising or expert reviews.\n\nOnce he identifies a brand that satisfies both his quality threshold and budget reality, he tends toward loyalty, reducing the cognitive burden of repeat decisions while preserving his hard-won sense of making smart, defensible choices."
      },
      "cultural_references_added": [
        "service center (Indian vernacular for electronics repair shops)",
        "Bengaluru as India's most expensive metro (regional economic context)",
        "online reviews and peer networks (authentic decision-making channels in urban India)"
      ],
      "contextual_examples_replaced": [
        {
          "original": "Repair costs ate up twice what I'd saved",
          "replacement": "Repair costs at the service center ate up twice what I'd saved",
          "attribute_source": "location.city + behavioral_pattern.quality_vs_budget"
        },
        {
          "original": "living alone in Bengaluru on a mid-level salary",
          "replacement": "living alone in Bengaluru, navigating the familiar early-career tension... in India's most expensive metro outside the National Capital Region",
          "attribute_source": "location.city + income_bracket + life_stage"
        }
      ],
      "validation_status": {
        "cr1_isolation": "pass",
        "cr2_stereotype_audit": "not_run",
        "cr3_cultural_realism": "not_run",
        "cr4_persona_fidelity": "not_run"
      },
      "skip_reason": null
    },
    {
      "enrichment_applied": true,
      "enrichment_provider": "sarvam",
      "enrichment_scope": "narrative_and_examples",
      "persona_id": "pg-pg-016",
      "enriched_narrative": {
        "first_person": "I've spent years building my own frameworks for deciding what's worth bringing into my home. After my postgraduate thesis at Cochin University \u2014 where I trusted teammates to deliver and watched the entire structure nearly collapse \u2014 I promised myself I'd verify everything myself. That instinct hasn't left me.\n\nBut here's what quietly exhausts me: I want to hand decisions off sometimes. My husband, a trusted colleague, even a well-reviewed brand on Flipkart or The Hindu's product guides. And occasionally I do. Then I'm back at my laptop at midnight, cross-checking ingredients on Nutrition labels, reading the third review page, confirming what I already suspected.\n\nPrice rarely stops me. If something is genuinely good, I'll pay for it. I'm not hunting discounts \u2014 I'm hunting certainty. When I find a brand that earns my trust through consistent quality, I stay. Switching feels like unnecessary risk. I'd rather deepen a relationship I've already validated myself.",
        "third_person": "Meghna Pillai is a 45-year-old biochemistry postgraduate from Kochi whose consumer behavior is fundamentally shaped by a formative academic experience at Cochin University that dismantled her confidence in external judgment. Having learned through a pivotal research episode that delegated work and institutional validation cannot be fully trusted, she has since internalized a rigorous self-verification process that governs nearly every significant decision she makes.\n\nHer analytical decision style \u2014 relatively moderate in intensity \u2014 reflects a careful, evidence-gathering orientation rather than impulsive action. She consistently prioritizes quality over price, treating cost as largely irrelevant when a product or service meets her exacting standards. What anchors her trust most powerfully is brand familiarity; established brands like Amul, Britannia, or Everest function as cognitive shortcuts that satisfy her need for reliability without requiring her to start evaluations from scratch. Once a brand earns her confidence through repeated quality delivery, her loyalty becomes exceptionally high \u2014 she does not switch lightly. The central psychological tension Meghna navigates is wanting to delegate while her past consistently pulls her back toward self-reliance."
      },
      "cultural_references_added": [
        "Cochin University (institution, location-specific)",
        "Flipkart (e-commerce platform, upper-middle income, relevant to decision-making)",
        "The Hindu (publication, Kerala-specific, credible review source for this demographic)",
        "Amul, Britannia, Everest (trusted Indian FMCG brands, Kerala/pan-Indian availability, upper-middle income consumer)",
        "Marine Drive (implicit in life story, Kochi-specific location)"
      ],
      "contextual_examples_replaced": [
