    {
      "enrichment_applied": true,
      "enrichment_provider": "sarvam",
      "enrichment_scope": "narrative_and_examples",
      "persona_id": "pg-pg-007",
      "enriched_narrative": {
        "first_person": "I've spent years building systems that don't fail \u2014 in my work, in my home, in every purchase I make. After that outsourced project unraveled spectacularly on my watch, I stopped assuming others would hold the same standards I do. So I research everything myself. GSMArena teardowns, detailed Amazon reviews, tech forums on Reddit at 11pm \u2014 that's just Tuesday for me. But here's what I can't ignore: I don't have infinite hours. My family of four has real needs, and sometimes I need to move faster than my due diligence allows. That's where brands I've already vetted become my shortcut. Sony, Bosch, Decathlon \u2014 they've earned my repeat business precisely because they've never made me regret trusting them. Price? Rarely the point. Getting it right the first time always costs less than fixing a mistake later.",
        "third_person": "Venkat Subramaniam is a 44-year-old postgraduate-educated tech professional in Bengaluru whose consumer behavior is deeply shaped by a formative professional failure \u2014 an outsourced project that unraveled catastrophically, leaving him with a hardened instinct to verify and control significant decisions himself. This experience explains why his trust anchor is firmly self-referential; he is reluctant to fully delegate judgment, even when intellectually drawn to the efficiency of doing so. His analytical decision style manifests as an ongoing need for more information before committing, driven less by price sensitivity \u2014 which is notably low \u2014 and more by a quality imperative that demands justification. He does not shop at D-Mart or Flipkart for the cheapest option; he shops for the best defensible one. What makes him particularly legible as a consumer type is his very high brand loyalty. Familiar, trusted brands like Sony or Bosch function as a cognitive proxy for the control he cannot always exercise directly. When a brand has earned his confidence, it effectively becomes a delegated decision he can live with \u2014 resolving his core tension between wanting oversight and needing to occasionally let go."
      },
      "cultural_references_added": [
        "GSMArena (Indian tech review platform widely used in Bengaluru)",
        "Amazon reviews (primary e-commerce review source for metro India)",
        "Reddit (English-language forum culture among postgraduate professionals)",
