    {
      "enrichment_applied": true,
      "enrichment_provider": "sarvam",
      "enrichment_scope": "narrative_and_examples",
      "persona_id": "pg-pg-005",
      "enriched_narrative": {
        "first_person": "I still think about that pram. We bought the cheaper one from some no-name brand at Hyderabad Central to save money, and within three months the wheel cracked while my wife was walking with our son in Banjara Hills. Nothing serious happened, thank god, but I replayed that moment for weeks. That incident rewired something in me permanently \u2014 cutting corners isn't saving money, it's borrowing trouble.\n\nBut here's my reality: I'm managing one income, a household of three in Hyderabad, and quality doesn't come cheap. So every major purchase becomes this exhausting internal negotiation. I research obsessively on Flipkart, cross-check specs, ask colleagues at the office what they bought and why. I need to know I'm getting genuine value, not just a convincing price tag.\n\nMy family is my filter for every decision. If there's any risk to them, the budget argument loses immediately. That's the line I won't cross again.",
        "third_person": "Siddharth Iyer is a 32-year-old postgraduate professional based in Hyderabad, navigating the financial pressures of early family life with a characteristic deliberateness that shapes nearly every significant purchase he makes. His analytical decision style \u2014 rooted in careful comparison rather than impulse \u2014 stems directly from lived experience. The budget pram purchased from an unvetted retailer left a lasting imprint: a compromise that backfired in public, reinforcing his conviction that low-cost alternatives carry hidden costs when family welfare is at stake.\n\nThis history creates a persistent internal tension. Siddharth genuinely values quality, yet his middle income and nuclear household responsibilities make budget constraints a constant reality. He resolves this tension by investing considerable time researching on e-commerce platforms and product review sites \u2014 seeking deals that do not require sacrificing standards. What accelerates his decision-making, however, is peer validation from colleagues and neighbours in his Hyderabad circles. His trust anchor is fundamentally relational: if someone he respects endorses a choice, the price-versus-value equation tilts more readily toward commitment."
      },
      "cultural_references_added": [
        "Hyderabad Central (retail location)",
        "Banjara Hills (locality-specific neighbourhood detail)",
