    {
      "enrichment_applied": true,
      "enrichment_provider": "sarvam",
      "enrichment_scope": "narrative_and_examples",
      "persona_id": "pg-pg-008",
      "enriched_narrative": {
        "first_person": "I always find myself standing in that same mental place \u2014 calculator in hand, heart wanting the best, wallet quietly reminding me of limits. After my daughter's pneumonia hospitalization cost us \u20b940,000, I stopped trusting that \"it'll work out.\" It never just works out. Now I research everything twice, ask my sister-in-law what she bought at D-Mart or BigBasket, check if my colleague had a similar experience. I'm not impulsive \u2014 I sit with decisions, sometimes too long. But for my daughter, I refuse to settle for cheap just because it's cheap. I want quality. Real quality. The problem is quality costs money we've carefully allocated elsewhere. So I look for that rare middle ground \u2014 something worth trusting, priced like someone actually understands my life. That's the only thing that earns my yes.",
        "third_person": "Anita Desai is a 31-year-old working mother in Delhi whose decision-making is fundamentally shaped by her daughter's unexpected hospitalization \u2014 a \u20b940,000 medical crisis that permanently recalibrated her relationship with money and risk. This singular experience explains why her analytical tendencies are consistently filtered through a lens of financial caution rather than pure logic.\n\nHer primary value is quality, yet her middle-class budget constraints create a persistent internal conflict she never fully resolves. Rather than defaulting to the cheapest option at D-Mart or BigBasket, Anita invests considerable cognitive effort in locating the intersection of affordability and reliability \u2014 a behavior rooted in protecting her nuclear family of three from the vulnerability she once experienced.\n\nNotably, Anita outsources uncertainty to her peer network and her Dwarka women's savings circle, where trusted voices provide emotional validation before she commits. Her family serves as her ultimate trust anchor, meaning purchases are measured against household benefit. She deliberates carefully before switching, preferring the known over the uncertain."
      },
